         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Two of the Salt-bushes, described as Atriplex nummularia and A. halimoides by Dr.  ¶ Lindley,  ¶ have mainly through my efforts become widely established in Africa. Professor  ¶ Lindley ¶ , my gene...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.03.00g</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Gardeners' Chronicle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'Australian salt bushes', </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>
                     <seg style="">, 4 May 1895, p. 559 (B</seg>95.05.01). It is introduced by 'Baron von <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Mueller</seg> writes:—'.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Two of the Salt-bushes, described as <name key="Atriplex%20nummularia">Atriplex nummularia</name> and A. halimoides by Dr. <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Lindley, </seg>have mainly through my efforts become widely established in Africa. Professor <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Lindley</seg>, my generous patron, described them from Sir Thomas Mitchell's collections.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As notes to Mitchell (1848), p. 64, and Mitchell (1838), vol. 1, p. 282, respectively.</p>
               </note> The English colonists have carried these two Atriplices from Capeland<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. the Cape Colony, South Africa.</p>
               </note> to beyond Transvaal, and the French colonists have brought them from the shores of the Mediterranean Sea to the Sahara and Senegal country by abundant gathering of seeds from the first plants raised. The importance of these shrubs cannot be over-estimated in regions free from severe frosts, particularly on somewhat saline soil, and in regions with little rainfall. Where (in the more central parts of Australia) these two Salsolaceous plants occur, the best merino wool is produced, the flocks need less water on account of the succulent foliage of the Atripices, and the hottest winds do not burn up these plants. I introduced both long ago also into Argentina,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to the Sociedad Rural Argentina, 10 February 1871 (in this edition as 71-02-10a)</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> the Southern States of North America, and several other countries.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Atriplex%20halimoides">Atriplex halimoides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Atriplex%20nummularia">Atriplex nummularia</name>
            </p>
